Then we play the "not guilty by
reason of insanity" card or even,

323
00:18:34,700 --> 00:18:36,949
if necessary, "guilty but insane".

324
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:40,009
I can't, Sean, I can't be in
the same room with him again.

325
00:18:40,010 --> 00:18:41,709
I get it.
You admire her.

326
00:18:41,710 --> 00:18:43,199
You want to be her when you grow up.

327
00:18:43,200 --> 00:18:44,509
The fact remains,

328
00:18:44,510 --> 00:18:46,479
if you can't make the accused
your focus

329
00:18:46,480 --> 00:18:48,039
then you shouldn't be
a defence lawyer,

330
00:18:48,040 --> 00:18:49,549
probably not
a criminal lawyer at all.

331
00:18:49,550 --> 00:18:50,850
Fine.

332
00:18:51,580 --> 00:18:53,930
- What?
- You're on your own.

333
00:20:34,640 --> 00:20:36,130
Open your mouth for me.

334
00:20:41,620 --> 00:20:43,210
Bring your teeth together.

335
00:20:45,030 --> 00:20:46,330
Painful?

336
00:20:46,990 --> 00:20:48,299
No, no.

337
00:20:48,300 --> 00:20:51,309
No crunching noises.
Any problems with vision?

338
00:20:51,310 --> 00:20:52,619
No.

339
00:20:52,620 --> 00:20:55,729
I think you have a minimally
displaced zygoma fracture.

340
00:20:55,730 --> 00:20:59,080
You're going to be on a soft diet
for two weeks or so.

341
00:20:59,950 --> 00:21:01,789
Though the bleeding's
impressive,

342
00:21:01,790 --> 00:21:03,610
the lacerations small.

343
00:21:04,040 --> 00:21:06,489
Might require a stitch or two.
Irrigate the wound

344
00:21:06,490 --> 00:21:09,219
with lots of normal saline
and I'll take a look.

345
00:21:09,220 --> 00:21:11,680
If you'd like to lie back on the bed
for me, please.

346
00:21:30,480 --> 00:21:32,680
- Any pain?
- Some.

347
00:21:33,110 --> 00:21:35,750
- Shall I check for blood in the urine?
- Yes, please.

348
00:21:44,480 --> 00:21:47,069
I'd like to keep you in overnight
for observation.

349
00:21:47,070 --> 00:21:49,209
- That won't be necessary.
- Don't worry,

350
00:21:49,210 --> 00:21:50,700
it'll just be bed and breakfast.

351
00:21:51,060 --> 00:21:53,090
I'll be back to stitch that eyebrow.

352
00:23:17,270 --> 00:23:19,900
Thought I'd look in on
you before I go.

353
00:23:21,390 --> 00:23:23,089
What time is it?

354
00:23:23,090 --> 00:23:24,770
Just after two.

355
00:23:26,230 --> 00:23:28,869
This is my ninth straight night
in a row.

356
00:23:28,870 --> 00:23:30,950
I've been on for 17 hours.

357
00:23:31,950 --> 00:23:33,560
Getting too old for this.

358
00:23:36,410 --> 00:23:38,780
I bet you're glad I saved his life.

359
00:23:44,830 --> 00:23:46,490
How's Tom Anderson?

360
00:23:47,020 --> 00:23:48,570
His arm's broken.

361
00:23:49,580 --> 00:23:51,289
He's undergone
a closed reduction

362
00:23:51,290 --> 00:23:53,379
to pull the bones
back into position.

363
00:23:53,380 --> 00:23:55,260
He's been sent home with
his arm in a cast.

364
00:23:57,730 --> 00:24:01,539
Given that you're less likely
to develop

365
00:24:01,540 --> 00:24:04,579
post-traumatic stress disorder
if you don't sleep

366
00:24:04,580 --> 00:24:07,260
after a bad experience,

367
00:24:07,970 --> 00:24:10,390
maybe I should...keep you awake
a wee bit longer at least.

368
00:24:12,400 --> 00:24:14,330
Don't you have a home to go to?

369
00:24:14,700 --> 00:24:17,739
I do. A wife and five kids,
as it happens,

370
00:24:17,740 --> 00:24:20,199
from a daughter of 12 to a son of
seven months.

371
00:24:20,200 --> 00:24:21,610
If I go home now,

372
00:24:22,240 --> 00:24:25,250
it'll be nappy changes
and the four o'clock feed.

373
00:24:25,720 --> 00:24:27,770
Might as well sit with you
for a bit.

374
00:24:29,310 --> 00:24:31,090
I'll ask you questions.

375
00:24:32,170 --> 00:24:33,930
- Really?
- Aye.

376
00:24:34,700 --> 00:24:36,000
Go on.

377
00:24:39,290 --> 00:24:41,290
Do you like flowers?

378
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:45,300
Of course.

379
00:24:46,100 --> 00:24:48,980
Can you play any musical instrument?

380
00:24:50,120 --> 00:24:53,050
I could play the violin
when I was a girl.

381
00:24:54,290 --> 00:24:55,889
Have you ever been happy?

382
00:24:55,890 --> 00:24:57,390
If so, when?

383
00:24:58,740 --> 00:25:00,450
When I was a child,

384
00:25:01,090 --> 00:25:02,690
before my father died.

385
00:25:07,690 --> 00:25:09,880
Have you any real friends?

386
00:25:11,930 --> 00:25:13,350
A few, yeah.

387
00:25:15,290 --> 00:25:17,160
Have you ever wished anyone dead?

388
00:25:18,440 --> 00:25:19,940
Yes, I have.

389
00:25:25,750 --> 00:25:28,020
Are you a good swimmer?

390
00:25:30,130 --> 00:25:31,430
Very.

391
00:25:32,550 --> 00:25:36,050
Are men or women the stronger,
do you think?

392
00:25:38,530 --> 00:25:41,610
- What do you think?
- Women, without a doubt.

393
00:25:42,810 --> 00:25:45,184
In fact, it's time you hurried up
and took over.

394
00:25:45,185 --> 00:25:47,550
I mean, it's going to happen so
why not get on with it?

395
00:25:49,680 --> 00:25:51,470
Which is your favourite season?

396
00:25:52,930 --> 00:25:54,230
Spring.

397
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:58,299
<i>Has Mr Spector been
a threat to himself</i>

398
00:25:58,300 --> 00:25:59,869
<i>or others in the past week?</i>

399
00:25:59,870 --> 00:26:01,869
There have been no more
breaches of protocol

400
00:26:01,870 --> 00:26:03,220
since he's been back.

401
00:26:04,180 --> 00:26:06,839
Anything more from the test results?

402
00:26:06,840 --> 00:26:10,129
Have you found any compelling
inconsistencies?

403
00:26:10,130 --> 00:26:11,719
No, I haven't.

404
00:26:11,720 --> 00:26:13,649
Which is unsurprising

405
00:26:13,650 --> 00:26:15,450
given his professional
knowledge.

406
00:26:17,470 --> 00:26:19,569
I know it's in your
nature to infer

407
00:26:19,570 --> 00:26:22,779
invisible unconscious processes
behind the memory loss

408
00:26:22,780 --> 00:26:25,339
and that it is an exceptional
doctor

409
00:26:25,340 --> 00:26:29,109
who will take the risk of concluding
in writing that someone

410
00:26:29,110 --> 00:26:31,000
is malingering
but,

411
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:32,700
with respect,

412
00:26:33,040 --> 00:26:35,180
that is what I think
you should do.

413
00:26:36,280 --> 00:26:38,439
- Do you?
- The CT head scan

414
00:26:38,440 --> 00:26:40,769
with and without
contrast was normal,

415
00:26:40,770 --> 00:26:43,329
the MRI of the brain
and the spinal

416
00:26:43,330 --> 00:26:45,099
cord showed normal results.

417
00:26:45,100 --> 00:26:47,519
There's no evidence of
structural brain damage

418
00:26:47,520 --> 00:26:50,280
in the neurological examinations
or neuroimaging.

419
00:26:50,780 --> 00:26:52,259
With his history of lying

420
00:26:52,260 --> 00:26:54,720
and everything
that he stands to gain

421
00:26:55,160 --> 00:26:58,440
from exaggeration
and fabrication of the symptoms,

422
00:26:59,750 --> 00:27:01,740
the amnesia has to be malingered.

423
00:27:03,050 --> 00:27:05,550
He's proved how dangerous he is.

424
00:27:06,260 --> 00:27:07,670
It has to be fake.

425
00:27:32,050 --> 00:27:33,350
It's not me.

426
00:27:33,970 --> 00:27:35,270
What?

427
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:39,880
I look at my body and it's not me.

428
00:27:40,810 --> 00:27:42,960
It'll take a while to get used to,
that's all.

429
00:28:02,150 --> 00:28:03,969
We've had a report,
ma'am,

430
00:28:03,970 --> 00:28:06,089
from the Juvenile Offenders'
Centre.

431
00:28:06,090 --> 00:28:07,939
It seems that Katie Benedetto

432
00:28:07,940 --> 00:28:09,650
has been self-harming.

433
00:28:10,050 --> 00:28:11,549
How?

434
00:28:11,550 --> 00:28:13,740
Cutting herself with
a piece of bone.

435
00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:15,509
What?

436
00:28:15,510 --> 00:28:16,919
They think she must
have found it

437
00:28:16,920 --> 00:28:18,420
in her food at some point.

438
00:28:20,080 --> 00:28:21,380
Jesus.

439
00:28:25,340 --> 00:28:28,679
<i>Is there a happy memory
from any part of your life</i>

440
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:29,980
<i>that you can remember?'</i>

441
00:28:39,810 --> 00:28:42,560
I used to think that there was
a black hole inside me

442
00:28:43,250 --> 00:28:44,600
that nothing could fill.

443
00:28:47,390 --> 00:28:48,910
Then I had a daughter.

444
00:28:51,860 --> 00:28:54,460
I remember the first time that
I put her to sleep.

445
00:28:56,200 --> 00:28:57,649
I was standing,

446
00:28:57,650 --> 00:28:59,160
holding her in my arms,

447
00:28:59,640 --> 00:29:00,980
rocking her.

448
00:29:02,890 --> 00:29:04,690
I was looking at her all the time.

449
00:29:05,410 --> 00:29:06,860
She was looking up at me.

450
00:29:09,370 --> 00:29:11,480
I began to feel
that she trusted me,

451
00:29:13,150 --> 00:29:14,490
that she felt safe.

452
00:29:16,980 --> 00:29:18,560
She must have done because

453
00:29:19,080 --> 00:29:20,710
her eyelids started closing...

454
00:29:22,420 --> 00:29:24,020
..little by little,

455
00:29:25,240 --> 00:29:26,640
and then she was asleep.

456
00:29:31,370 --> 00:29:32,670
That's a good memory.

457
00:29:36,090 --> 00:29:38,260
Why did you attack Stella Gibson?

458
00:29:39,830 --> 00:29:42,380
Why did you break that
young man's arm?

459
00:29:52,600 --> 00:29:56,150
There is a visible
and an invisible world.

460
00:29:57,380 --> 00:29:59,010
That's why people get hurt.

461
00:30:08,960 --> 00:30:10,290
Do you think I'm treatable?

462
00:30:12,960 --> 00:30:14,260
Of course.

463
00:30:16,860 --> 00:30:18,160
Curable?

464
00:30:21,730 --> 00:30:23,110
That's different.

465
00:30:33,020 --> 00:30:35,110
What would you do for me
if I was your patient?

466
00:30:39,260 --> 00:30:41,639
Try to get you to pay attention

467
00:30:41,640 --> 00:30:44,140
wisely to things as they are.

468
00:30:45,730 --> 00:30:47,560
Foster clear thinking

469
00:30:48,080 --> 00:30:49,560
and open-heartedness.

470
00:30:51,010 --> 00:30:54,009
Try to develop the capacity
in you

471
00:30:54,010 --> 00:30:56,559
to experience a feeling without

472
00:30:56,560 --> 00:30:58,100
necessarily acting on it.

473
00:30:58,970 --> 00:31:02,049
Try to enable you to see
the difference between

474
00:31:02,050 --> 00:31:03,700
thoughts and reality.

475
00:31:10,150 --> 00:31:11,980
I'd imagine you're a good father.

476
00:31:12,660 --> 00:31:14,790
What do you mean by "good father"?

477
00:31:19,610 --> 00:31:21,000
Someone who is present,

478
00:31:23,010 --> 00:31:24,340
there for his children.

479
00:31:36,490 --> 00:31:38,759
<i>Has anyone ever told you
you sometimes have</i>

480
00:31:38,760 --> 00:31:40,889
<i>bad dreams that you
can't remember?</i>

481
00:31:40,890 --> 00:31:43,100
Has your mummy or your daddy
ever told you that?

482
00:31:43,530 --> 00:31:45,359
Yes.
Mummy took me

483
00:31:45,360 --> 00:31:47,120
to the doctor's one time.

484
00:31:48,290 --> 00:31:49,599
Have you had any bad dreams

485
00:31:49,600 --> 00:31:51,649
since you've been staying
with Joan and Stephen?

486
00:31:51,650 --> 00:31:53,240
I don't think so.

487
00:31:53,650 --> 00:31:55,530
She hasn't.
She's been sleeping well.

488
00:31:56,180 --> 00:31:58,339
Daddy said he had bad dreams
like mine when

489
00:31:58,340 --> 00:32:00,050
he was in the children's home.

490
00:32:01,450 --> 00:32:02,880
Did he?

491
00:32:03,630 --> 00:32:05,220
Did he say
what he dreamed about?

492
00:32:05,780 --> 00:32:07,230
Frightening things.

493
00:32:09,410 --> 00:32:12,180
How do you feel about your daddy
right now, Olivia?

494
00:32:13,420 --> 00:32:14,730
I love him.

495
00:32:15,330 --> 00:32:16,630
But?

496
00:32:16,940 --> 00:32:19,340
I don't think I'll go see him
for a while.

497
00:32:22,310 --> 00:32:24,369
How long do you think before
you'll see him again?

498
00:32:24,370 --> 00:32:25,909
When I'm grown up I might.

499
00:32:25,910 --> 00:32:27,490
Or if I have a baby.

500
00:32:28,310 --> 00:32:31,100
If I have a baby,
I might go take her to see him.

501
00:32:33,670 --> 00:32:35,240
<i>What happened to your face?</i>

502
00:32:36,570 --> 00:32:38,440
I was in a car accident.

503
00:32:41,210 --> 00:32:42,510
No, I wasn't.

504
00:32:46,140 --> 00:32:47,840
Paul Spector attacked me.

505
00:32:55,910 --> 00:32:57,590
I've got marks like that.

506
00:33:05,260 --> 00:33:07,730
- Show me.
- I can't.

507
00:33:08,290 --> 00:33:09,720
Why?

508
00:33:10,330 --> 00:33:13,390
They're on my upper thighs and on
the soles of my feet.

509
00:33:15,860 --> 00:33:17,550
I didn't want anyone to know,

510
00:33:18,080 --> 00:33:19,380
to see them.

511
00:33:20,430 --> 00:33:21,790
They were private.

512
00:33:24,410 --> 00:33:25,780
Why did you do it?

513
00:33:28,940 --> 00:33:30,910
I think for the same reason you do.

514
00:33:33,620 --> 00:33:34,920
What's that?

515
00:33:35,450 --> 00:33:36,750
Anger.

516
00:33:40,330 --> 00:33:42,320
What did you have to be angry about?

517
00:33:44,080 --> 00:33:45,380
My father.

518
00:33:49,160 --> 00:33:50,570
Why?

519
00:33:52,480 --> 00:33:53,780
He died.

520
00:33:56,770 --> 00:33:58,190
How?

521
00:34:00,850 --> 00:34:02,150
He was ill.

522
00:34:04,780 --> 00:34:06,190
How old were you?

523
00:34:07,090 --> 00:34:08,390
14.

524
00:34:15,310 --> 00:34:16,880
My father killed himself.

525
00:34:17,580 --> 00:34:19,150
I thought it was an accident.

526
00:34:21,930 --> 00:34:23,820
He chose to ride a motorbike.

527
00:34:25,900 --> 00:34:28,370
Even though I worried about him
every time he went out...

528
00:34:30,400 --> 00:34:32,140
..every night he was late home.

529
00:34:37,040 --> 00:34:39,240
He loved the bike more than
he loved me.

530
00:34:41,880 --> 00:34:43,279
Loved the thrill of speed

531
00:34:43,280 --> 00:34:45,110
more than he loved
his only daughter.

532
00:34:47,480 --> 00:34:49,200
I don't call that an accident.

533
00:34:51,610 --> 00:34:53,790
Is that why you're throwing
your life away?

534
00:34:56,690 --> 00:34:58,430
You know you can't get him back.

